Abstract

This dissertation presents the complete mathematical and architectural foundations of E4 Tech-Support, a humanoid autonomous service robot whose cognitive architecture is formally proven to satisfy the six axioms of Operationally Stable Intelligence (OSI) as defined by the Fractal Capsule Intelligence (FCI) framework. The central contribution is a fully specified theoretical system: every layer of E4's intelligence, from sensor fusion to meta-cognitive self-modeling, is defined by rigorous mathematical formalisms with accompanying stability proofs. The cognitive layer is organized as a four-nucleus Specialized Agent Orchestration Architecture (SAOA) with Hamiltonian coupling dynamics proven to converge to a unique consensus fixed point. The diagnostic nucleus implements a fully specified symbolic-neural hybrid with hysteresis-controlled structural plasticity. The Fractal Intelligence Quotient (FIQ) is operationalized as a computable metric with each component rigorously defined: computational efficiency, dynamical stability, representational richness (via correlation dimension of capsule trajectories), and self-consistency. All claims are supported by formal proofs rather than empirical experimentation, establishing E4 as the first physically instantiable system with provable OSI compliance.

