Chapter 2: Background and Related Work

2.1 Mathematical Frameworks for Intelligent Systems

Banach fixed-point theory (Banach, 1922) provides the foundation for contraction mappings in cognitive architectures. Lyapunov stability theory underpins convergence analysis for dynamical systems. Information geometry (Amari, 2016) supplies the tools for analyzing belief manifolds in neural representations. Renormalization group theory (Wilson, 1975) motivates the self-similarity across scales in hierarchical architectures. These mathematical foundations are invoked throughout the FCI framework.

2.2 Prior Architectures: Limitations in Formal Grounding

Rule-based expert systems (Davis et al., 1977) lack formal guarantees of completeness or consistency beyond their rule sets. Bayesian networks (Pearl, 1988) provide probabilistic semantics but no mechanism for structural adaptation. Deep learning architectures (LeCun et al., 2015) lack provable stability bounds and exhibit adversarial vulnerability. Multi-agent systems (Wooldridge, 2009) typically lack convergence guarantees for inter-agent coordination. The E4 architecture addresses each limitation through its axiomatic grounding in FCI.

2.3 Fractal Capsule Intelligence: Axiomatic Framework

FCI (Maakoul, 2025) proposes six necessary and jointly sufficient conditions for OSI:

· Axiom 1 (Hierarchical Representation): The system must represent information at multiple scales with explicit part-whole relationships.
· Axiom 2 (Recursive Transformation): Representations must be updated by recursive operators that contract uncertainty.
· Axiom 3 (Self-Similarity): The same computational motif must recur across scales.
· Axiom 4 (Contraction Stability): The composite representation operator must be a contraction mapping.
· Axiom 5 (Fixed-Point Closure): The system must converge to a unique fixed point for each input.
· Axiom 6 (Meta-Recursion): The system must maintain a model of its own operation.

The Compliance Regime — spectral normalization, timescale separation, convergent routing — provides sufficient conditions for a capsule architecture to satisfy all six axioms. This dissertation proves that E4, under its specified parameters, satisfies the Compliance Regime and therefore constitutes an OSI instance.

