Chapter 7: Self-Diagnostics — Recursive Self-Modeling (Axiom 6)

7.1 Self-Model Architecture

E4 maintains a self-model $\mathcal{M}_{\text{self}}$ implemented as a separate lightweight capsule network with architecture:

· Input: Raw sensor observations $z_t$ (concatenated and downsampled)
· Output: Predicted nucleus outputs $\hat{y}_k(t)$ for each $k \in \{V, D, P, M\}$
· Training: End-to-end supervised learning during simulation phase, with targets $y_k(t)$ from the actual nuclei

The self-model has its own weight matrices $W_{\text{self}}$, also spectrally normalized. It operates on a slower timescale than the operational nuclei:

· Operational nuclei update at 100Hz
· Self-model updates at 1Hz (online fine-tuning)
· Self-model weight updates at 0.01Hz (slow meta-learning)

This timescale separation is a key condition in the FCI Compliance Regime: the meta-level adapts slowly enough that it does not destabilize the base-level dynamics.

7.2 Divergence Monitoring

At each timestep $t$, compute for each nucleus $k$:

\delta_k(t) = \| y_k(t) - \hat{y}_k(t) \|_2

where $y_k(t)$ is the actual nucleus output (e.g., for Nucleus V, the scene graph encoded as a vector; for Nucleus D, the fault distribution vector).

Detection threshold: $\epsilon_k = 3 \sigma_k$, where $\sigma_k$ is the standard deviation of $\delta_k$ during nominal operation (estimated from an initial calibration phase). By Chebyshev's inequality, under nominal conditions $P(\delta_k > 3\sigma_k) \leq 1/9 \approx 0.11$. A sustained exceedance is required for alert.

7.3 Graduated Response Protocol

Let $T_{\text{alert}} = 10$ timesteps (0.1 seconds at 100Hz). Define:

· Level 1 ($\epsilon_k < \delta_k < 2\epsilon_k$ for $T_{\text{alert}}$ consecutive steps): Increase Nucleus $k$'s sampling rate; flag its outputs as low-confidence in downstream nuclei.
· Level 2 ($2\epsilon_k \leq \delta_k < 3\epsilon_k$ for $T_{\text{alert}}$): Suspend Nucleus $k$; redistribute its function via Hamiltonian coupling (other nuclei adjust their beliefs to compensate).
· Level 3 ($\delta_k \geq 3\epsilon_k$ for $T_{\text{alert}}$): Halt operation; request human intervention.

Theorem 7.1 (Detection Bounds): Under the assumption that $\delta_k(t)$ is a stationary process with finite variance under nominal conditions, the probability of false alarm (Level 3 trigger under nominal conditions) is bounded by:

P(\text{false alarm}) \leq \left( \frac{\sigma_k^2}{(3\sigma_k)^2} \right)^{T_{\text{alert}}} = \left( \frac{1}{9} \right)^{10} \approx 2.8 \times 10^{-10}

Proof: By Chebyshev's inequality, $P(\delta_k(t) \geq 3\sigma_k) \leq 1/9$ at any single timestep. For $T_{\text{alert}}$ consecutive independent timesteps (worst-case bound), the probability of all exceeding threshold is $(1/9)^{10}$. $\blacksquare$

This extremely low false alarm probability ensures that Level 3 alerts are virtually always genuine degradations.

7.4 Formal Satisfaction of Axiom 6

Definition 7.1 (Meta-Recursion): A system satisfies Axiom 6 if it maintains a model $\mathcal{M}$ of its own operation and uses $\mathcal{M}$ to regulate its behavior.

Theorem 7.2 (E4 Satisfies Axiom 6): The self-model $\mathcal{M}_{\text{self}}$, divergence monitoring, and graduated response protocol constitute a model of E4's own operation used for regulation, thereby satisfying Axiom 6.

Proof: By construction: $\mathcal{M}_{\text{self}}$ predicts nucleus outputs; divergence monitoring compares predictions to actuals; graduated response modifies system behavior (sampling rates, suspension, halting) based on divergence. This is precisely the definition of meta-recursive regulation. $\blacksquare$

