Chapter 8: Manipulation and Control — Contraction Analysis

8.1 Kinematics and Inverse Kinematics

For a six-DOF manipulator, forward kinematics:

T_{0n}(q) = \prod_{i=1}^6 A_i(q_i)

where $A_i$ are DH transformation matrices. Inverse kinematics is solved via damped least squares:

\dot{q} = J^\dagger(q) \dot{x}, \quad J^\dagger = J^T(JJ^T + \lambda^2 I)^{-1}

Adaptive damping: $\lambda = \lambda_0$ when $\sigma_{\min}(J) > \epsilon$, $\lambda = \lambda_{\max}$ when $\sigma_{\min}(J) \leq \epsilon$, ensuring bounded joint velocities near singularities.

8.2 Joint-Level Control

PID control law:

u(t) = K_p e(t) + K_i \int_0^t e(\tau) d\tau + K_d \dot{e}(t)

The closed-loop dynamics are:

M(q)\ddot{q} + C(q, \dot{q})\dot{q} + g(q) = u(t)

Theorem 8.1 (Joint-Level Stability): For sufficiently large $K_d$ satisfying $K_d > \frac{1}{2}\|\dot{M}(q, \dot{q})\|_2$ for all $(q, \dot{q})$ in the workspace, the PID-controlled manipulator is globally asymptotically stable.

Proof: Lyapunov function $V = \frac{1}{2}\dot{q}^T M(q) \dot{q} + \frac{1}{2}e^T K_p e$ yields $\dot{V} = -\dot{q}^T (K_d - \frac{1}{2}\dot{M})\dot{q} - e^T K_i \int e \, dt \leq 0$, with equality only at the desired setpoint. LaSalle's theorem gives global asymptotic stability. $\blacksquare$

8.3 Grasp Planning with Formal Quality Bounds

For a candidate grasp $g$ on object point cloud $O$, the Dex-Net quality metric:

Q(g, O) = P(\text{success} | g, O) \cdot \text{FC}(g)

where $P(\text{success})$ is estimated by a GQ-CNN and $\text{FC}(g)$ is the force-closure metric.

Theorem 8.2 (Force-Closure Condition): A grasp $g$ achieves force-closure iff there exists $\epsilon > 0$ such that for all $\|w\| \leq \epsilon$, there exist contact forces satisfying equilibrium. This is equivalent to the origin being in the interior of the convex hull of the primitive wrench cones.

Proof: Standard result from multi-fingered grasping theory (Murray et al., 1994). $\blacksquare$

For precision tasks, we augment with alignment score:

Q_{\text{precision}}(g, p) = Q(g, O) \cdot \exp\left(-\frac{\|\theta_g - \theta_p\|^2}{2\sigma^2}\right)

where $\theta_g$ is grasp approach angle and $\theta_p$ is target port orientation from scene graph.

