Appendix B: Derivation of $\text{FIQ}_{\max}$ for E4 Architecture

B.1 Component Upper Bounds

The FIQ components are defined in Chapter 9. We derive theoretical maxima given architectural constraints.

E (Efficiency): $E = 1 - T_{\text{task}} / T_{\text{max}}$. The minimum possible task time $T_{\text{task}}$ is bounded by physical limits (sensor acquisition, computation, motor movement). Let $T_{\min}$ be the irreducible time (e.g., 1 second for a simple diagnostic). Then $E_{\max} = 1 - T_{\min}/T_{\max}$. For $T_{\max} = 600$ s (human upper bound) and $T_{\min} \approx 10$ s (from simulation studies), $E_{\max} \approx 0.983$.

Λ (Stability): $\Lambda = 1 - \text{CV}^2$. The minimum achievable coefficient of variation is limited by sensor noise and motor precision. In simulation, $\text{CV}_{\min} \approx 0.05$, giving $\Lambda_{\max} = 1 - 0.0025 = 0.9975$.

F (Representational Richness): $F = \min(1, d_C / d_{\text{max}})$ with $d_{\text{max}} = 16$. The correlation dimension $d_C$ cannot exceed the embedding dimension of the capsule space (16). Under ideal conditions, the system might explore the full 16-dimensional manifold, giving $d_C = 16$ and $F_{\max} = 1$.

P (Self-Consistency): $P = 1 - \frac{1}{4} \sum_k \bar{\delta}_k / \delta_{\text{max}}$. Perfect self-prediction ($\bar{\delta}_k = 0$) gives $P_{\max} = 1$.

B.2 Combined Upper Bound

Taking the geometric mean:

\text{FIQ}_{\max} = (0.983 \times 0.9975 \times 1 \times 1)^{1/4} = (0.9805)^{1/4} \approx 0.995.

However, this bound is not achievable simultaneously because the components are not independent: achieving $d_C = 16$ may require exploratory actions that increase task time (reducing $E$) or increase variance (reducing $\Lambda$). A more realistic bound comes from information-theoretic trade-offs. Using the concept of Pareto optimality, we can derive an upper bound from the constraint that the system must satisfy the FIR axioms. A detailed analysis using the Cramér-Rao bound for estimation and the entropy rate of the capsule dynamics yields $\text{FIQ}_{\max} \approx 0.89$ (see Appendix B.3 for derivation). This matches the value cited in Chapter 10.

