Appendix C: Lipschitz Constants for E4 Components

C.1 Definitions

For a mapping $f: \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{Y}$ between normed spaces, the Lipschitz constant $L_f$ is the smallest number such that $\|f(x_1) - f(x_2)\|_{\mathcal{Y}} \le L_f \|x_1 - x_2\|_{\mathcal{X}}$ for all $x_1, x_2$. Lipschitz constants are used in convergence proofs (e.g., to bound step sizes in gradient descent) and stability analysis.

C.2 Component-Wise Constants

Component Lipschitz Constant Derivation / Reference
EKF prediction step $f(\hat{x}, u)$ $L_f = \|F_t\|_2 \le 1 + \Delta t \cdot \|A\|_2$ Jacobian $F_t$ of motion model; bounded by maximum velocity
EKF update (Kalman gain) $K_t(z)$ $L_K \le \|P H^T (H P H^T + R)^{-1}\|_2$ From matrix gain formula; bounded by $\|P\|_2 \|H\|_2 / \lambda_{\min}(R)$
Capsule layer (EM routing) $L_{\text{EM}} \le \prod_l \|W_l\|_2$ Composition of linear transforms and squash; spectral normalization ensures $\|W_l\|_2 \le 1$, so $L_{\text{EM}} \le 1$
Hamiltonian gradient $\nabla H$ $L_{\nabla H} \le \max_k \|\nabla^2 U_k\|_2 + 4\gamma \max \|\nabla^2 \Phi\|_2$ From Hessian bounds; for E4, $L_{\nabla H} \approx 50$ (Section 10.2)
PID controller mapping $u = \text{PID}(e)$ $L_{\text{PID}} \le K_p + K_i \Delta t + K_d / \Delta t$ From discrete-time PID formulation
Grasp quality $Q(g, O)$ $L_Q \le \max \|\nabla_g Q\|_2$ Bounded by GQ-CNN gradient; in practice $\approx 10$

C.3 Use in Convergence Proofs

For gradient descent (Algorithm 1), the step size $\alpha$ must satisfy $\alpha < 2/L_{\nabla H}$ to guarantee convergence. With $L_{\nabla H} \approx 50$, we get $\alpha < 0.04$, consistent with Section 10.2. For the EKF, Lipschitz constants ensure bounded error propagation.

