Appendix D: Hamiltonian Coupling – Equivalence and Convergence Proofs

D.1 Equivalence of Algorithm 1 to Damped Hamiltonian Dynamics

We restate Algorithm 1:

```
q_k(t+1) = q_k(t) - α (∇_{q_k} U_k + γ Σ_{j≠k} ∇_{q_k} D_JS(P_j, P_k)) - β p_k(t)
p_k(t+1) = p_k(t) - α (∇_{q_k} U_k + γ Σ_{j≠k} ∇_{q_k} D_JS(P_j, P_k))
```

Let $F_k = -\nabla_{q_k} U_k - γ Σ_{j≠k} \nabla_{q_k} D_JS(P_j, P_k)$ be the total force (negative gradient of $H$ with respect to $q_k$). Then the update is:

q_k(t+1) = q_k(t) + α F_k(t) - β p_k(t)


p_k(t+1) = p_k(t) + α F_k(t)

This is a symplectic Euler discretization of the damped Hamiltonian equations:

\dot{q}_k = p_k


\dot{p}_k = F_k - β p_k

with step size $α$. The local truncation error is $O(α^2)$ (Hairer et al., 2006). Thus Algorithm 1 approximates the continuous dynamics.

D.2 Convergence to Fixed Point

Define the Lyapunov function $L(t) = H(q(t), p(t))$. For the continuous system, $\dot{L} = -β \sum_k \|p_k\|^2 \le 0$, with equality only when all $p_k = 0$ (i.e., at a fixed point). For the discrete system, with sufficiently small $α$, $L(t+1) - L(t) \le -c α β \sum_k \|p_k(t)\|^2$ for some $c > 0$, ensuring decrease until $p_k \to 0$. Once $p_k = 0$, the dynamics reduce to gradient descent on $U_k + γ \sum_{j≠k} D_JS$, which by strict convexity (Theorem 5.2) converges to the unique minimizer $q^*$. Formal proof uses the discrete LaSalle invariance principle (Mei et al., 2016).

